 been facing acute power crisis and the situation is even worse for the tribal families who live in remote villages. Kumaria, one such remote village located in Gumla administrative block, has power only for 3-4 hours every day. The residents of this village burn kerosene wick lamps for light after sunset. When the kerosene stock runs out they live in darkness. The village has small irrigation pumps which are being powered with the pollution causing fuels like kerosene and diesel.To get out of this crisis, 120 tribal families that live in Kumaria have come together and decided to install a solar power grid in their village in order to have access to electricity for their basic necessities. They have approached Mlinda to install a village grid. Mlinda would commission the village grid, own, run and operate the facility. All connections will be metered and villagers will pay as per consumption. Villagers prepay based on their energy requirement. Each of these 120 tribal households will get power for five hours in the evening and one hour before dawn. Each of the small irrigation pumps will get power for four hours during daytime. Village grid will also power productive needs for four hours during daytime. Villagers can prepay from direct savings accrued from non-usage of kerosene and diesel. Also, these additional savings can then be invested into their children\'s education and also to grow their businesses.The grid system costs Rs.75, 00,000. Mlinda has raised 50% of the project cost. Hence, Mlinda is seeking a loan of Rs.37, 50,000/- to install a 25 KW solar-based village grid with diesel backup. The families intend to repay this loan within 34 months.Your loan will help these disadvantaged tribal households get access to clean energy, healthier life and affordable electricity.',0,13,0,3,1,24,19,102,'Beed, Maharashtra 431122, India','Beed ','18.9890893','75.76007849999996','2016-08-04','2016-08-05','0000-00-00 00:00:00',8300.00,0.31,2711141.00,10.00,0,0.00,0.00,495